<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WEEK AHEAD: ABIDJAN; 
</P>
<P>
AN AFRICAN FIRST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A milestone in African democracy could be reached during presidential elections 
Sunday in Ivory Coast. 
</P>
<P>
The nearly 90-year-old Felix Houphouet-Boigny, the West African country's only 
president in 30 years of independence, will face his first independent 
challenger ever, 45-year-old history professor Laurent Gbagbo. 
</P>
<P>
The challenger is a decided underdog, in part because he has been denied 
adequate access to the government-owned media. Beyond that, however, observers 
say Gbagbo's campaign has been largely undisturbed by government interference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
IVORY COAST -- ELECTIONS; HOUPHOUET BOIGNY, FELIX 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
