<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WEEK AHEAD: TIRANA; 
</P>
<P>
HERMIT TURNS HOST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Long locked in a time warp of hard-line Stalinism, Albania emerges from its 
isolation Wednesday to host a meeting of foreign ministers from the volatile 
Balkan states. 
</P>
<P>
Tirana's hospitality is aimed at gaining credibility and support for its first, 
tentative steps toward joining European security accords and establishing 
diplomatic ties with an outside world it spurned for decades. 
</P>
<P>
The meeting will bring together officials from some of the most troubled 
nations on the continent in hopes that peaceful solutions can be found for the 
conflicts threatening civil war and economic collapse in the historically 
fractious region. Attending will be representatives from Albania, Bulgaria, 
Greece, Romania, Turkey and Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
ALBANIA -- FOREIGN POLICY; ALBANIA -- FOREIGN RELATIONS -- EUROPE 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
