<HEADLINE>
<P>
HIGHER R&amp;D COSTS KEEP NET EARNINGS DOWN AT BECKMAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MICHAEL FLAGG, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
FULLERTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Citing greater research and development expenditures, Beckman Instruments Inc. 
said Monday that net earnings increased only 2.1% to $9.6 million in the third 
quarter from $9.4 million for the same three-month period in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Beckman, a manufacturer of medical diagnostic equipment, said 
sales increased to $201 million for the quarter ended Sept. 30, up 7.7% from 
$186.7 million in the third quarter of last year. 
</P>
<P>
Net earnings for the first three quarters of the year dropped to $26.2 million 
from $31.5 million. Sales for the nine months were up slightly to $589.4 
million from $586.2 million last year. 
</P>
<P>
The company blamed slow sales this year on limited budgets at publicly funded 
research laboratories, which are some of the Fullerton-based company's biggest 
customers. There are fewer research grants available to those labs, the company 
said, so they're not purchasing as much equipment. 
</P>
<P>
Some labs, too, are leasing equipment from Beckman rather than purchasing it 
outright, which "has had the effect of stretching out sales revenues" over 
longer periods of time, said Beckman President Lou Rosso in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
Net income for the first nine months of the year was down in part because the 
company has increased its research and development budget to $59.7 million 
during the first three quarters, a 17% increase from last year. 
</P>
<P>
New products from this research should help Beckman expand its market share 
"during a time of relatively weak demand" for diagnostic equipment, Rosso said. 
</P>
<P>
The company's stock closed at $12.75, up 12.5 cents in trading Monday on the 
New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
BECKMAN'S FINANCIAL PERFORMANCE 
</P>
<P>
In the third quarter, Beckman Instruments reported a 7.7% increase in revenues 
and a 2.1% increase in net earnings. Figures are in millions, except amounts 
per share 
</P>
<P>
Figures are in thousands except per share data. 
</P>
